[normal]WRITTEN EVIDENCE SUBMITTED BY HAND IN HAND: CENTER FOR JEWISH-ARAB EDUCATION IN ISRAEL[bold] (HIH)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]SUMMARY [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Hand in Hand’s Mission
[normal] 
[normal]1. 
[normal]The mission of Hand in Hand: The Center for Jewish-Arab Education in Israel (HIH) is to create a strong and inclusive shared society in Israel by (1) enabling Jewish and Arab children to study together in bilingual schools with a multicultural educational model that teaches respect and tolerance, and (2) developing community leadership and a range of community building events for Jewish and Arab adults which creates a social movement beyond the walls of the school.  Starting in 1998 with two schools and 50 children, HIH in 2013-14 has grown to five bilingual schools (Jerusalem, Galilee, Wadi Ara, Haifa, and Jaffa) and 1,080 Jewish and Arab students in grades K-12. Around each school HIH is developing a framework of shared community events to build an integrated and inclusive community. This is a singular accomplishment in a society that generally finds Arabs and Jews living apart, studying in separate institutions, and having minimal contact
[normal], a situation which fosters mistrust, reinforces stereotypes, and perpetuates conflict between the two groups.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conflict 
[normal]resolution requires daily interaction
[normal]2. 
[normal]Resolution of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict will require political creativity and resolve, but it cannot succeed without both sides 
[normal]recognizing the legitimacy of the other nation and the other’s 
[normal]narrative. HIH fo
[normal]cuses its efforts on the Jewish and Arab citizens of Israel (the latter often considering themselves Palestinian citizens as well).  The creation of an inclusive society between Jews and Arabs living within Israel’s current borders
[normal] is contingent upon both 
[normal]sides legitimating the other.  This process of mutual 
[normal]recognition will 
[normal]improve 
[normal]relations and understanding between Jews and Arabs in Israel
[normal], and illustrate the viability of shared living.  This is applicable 
[normal]not only 
[normal]to Jews and Arabs in Israel but 
[normal]to 
[normal]Israelis and Palestini
[normal]a
[normal]ns
[normal] on both sides of the conflict as well.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. 
[normal]Bringing the 
[normal]Jewish and Arab 
[normal]populations together periodically for coexistence encounters and dialogue has proven to be insufficient. Daily contact starting in pre-kindergarten, in a sa
[normal]fe environment where ongoing relationships and friendships can be developed is crucial. Providing the tools to deal with differences in per
[normal]s
[normal]pectives is vital.
[normal] 
[normal]Hand in Hand believes that the 
[normal]daily
[normal], positive
[normal] 
[normal]and meaningful 
[normal]interaction
[normal] 
[normal]of its 
[normal]Jewish and 
[normal]A
[normal]rab
[normal] students
[normal], teachers, 
[normal]and 
[normal]parents 
[normal]taking place in 
[normal]its bilingual schools
[normal],
[normal] and
[normal] 
[normal]the connections 
[normal]and social awareness 
[normal]being developed 
[normal]between community members 
[normal]as a 
[normal]result
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]community 
[normal]building events
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]will create 
[normal]shared social and civic frameworks between Jews and
[normal] Arabs
[normal] that
[normal] 
[normal]will 
[normal]alter Israeli society
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal]. 
[normal]HIH bilingual schools are amongst the only places in Israel where Jews and Arabs engage 
[normal]on a daily basis
[normal] in an environment of mutual respect, with Hebrew and Arabic-speaking teachers, a shared calendar to celebrate the holidays of each culture, as well as a multicultural curriculum. 
[normal]O
[normal]ur students excel academically, 
[normal]winning competitions in science and spelli
[normal]ng bees, and achieving above average scores on the matriculation exams.
[normal] HIH’s bilingual multicultural educational model also 
[normal]fosters understanding and friendship while breaking down barriers between Arab and Jewish youth, and promotes civic responsibility 
[normal]in its students. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Special Elements in HIH Schools
[normal]5
[normal]. 
[normal]Although 
[normal]Hand in Hand schools 
[normal]are
[normal] 
[normal]approved, supervised and supported by the 
[normal]Ministry of Education, 
[normal]Hand in Hand 
[normal]must raise
[normal] 
[normal]an 
[normal]additional 
[normal]$
[normal]2.7
[normal] million
[normal] 
[normal]in order to add
[normal] special elements to promote the bilingual education and social values that are its reason for being:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The events that happened in Gaza and the south in 2008, was the first time that I personally had to deal with a politically sensitive issue as a mature person... Going to school that same day was difficult, but …the teachers had all kinds of activities pre
[normal]pared to help us discuss our feelings and thoughts, and I felt my opinions were heard and respected by all students. This experience was important to me, because it tested the true values of the school, and I realized that things happen and they might be t
[normal]ough, but we are equipped with the best tools to handle them, by listening and respecting. I think this has really shown me that we don’t live in a bubble where everything is perfect, we live in the real world, where horrible things happen sometimes, but w
[normal]e learn how to handle them in the best way. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Role of HIH’s Education Department
[normal]6
[normal]. 
[normal]Achieving academic excellence and promoting civic responsibility at HIH schools requires properly trained staff 
[normal]who
[normal] can 
[normal]provide 
[normal]civic and 
[normal]pedagogical leadership, 
[normal]utilize 
[normal]HIH’s unique co-teaching model and can implement multicultural curricula which teach tolerance and civic responsibility.
[normal] 
[normal]To this end, HIH has created an Education Department
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]HIH teachers
[normal], both veteran and new,
[normal] 
[normal]receive 
[normal]special pedagogic training
[normal] 
[normal]so that they are able to 
[normal]work 
[normal]as equals 
[normal]with
[normal]in
[normal] the co-teaching model, 
[normal]learn to integrate
[normal] both the core and supplementary curricula i
[normal]nto their teaching, and 
[normal]are equipped to
[normal] manage
[normal] the issues of culture and difference that arise.  
[normal]This training 
[normal]involves both working closely with 
[normal]individual 
[normal]staff in particula
[normal]r
[normal] schools
[normal],
[normal] as well as
[normal] bringing the educational staff from all 
[normal]of 
[normal]HIH’s 
[normal]country-wide network of 
[normal]schools together for an intensive three-day conference 
[normal]in order 
[normal]to
[normal] share ideas, problem solve, and learn from each other’s experiences
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]S
[normal]ince HIH’s Jewish and Arab teachers are essentially civic leaders who are training the next generation, it is vital that the teaching staff from 
[normal]all
[normal] five HIH bilingual schools strategize together as to the best practices for achieving their goals.
[normal] 
